Supplementary A: Performance-Metric Findings [Continued]
A.1. Model Predictive Performance for 1-Month SPEI
In Table S1, GBM and XG again clearly emerge as the best-performing models. These two methods reduce average RMSE to the 0.03–0.04 band and MAE to 0.026–0.029, while yielding average R² values of 0.997–0.999, i.e., near-perfect outcomes. The very high inter-station consistency indicates that these boosting-based approaches are highly reliable for short-horizon (1-month) SPEI forecasts.
The LSTM method delivers strong performance with average RMSE ≈ 0.179, MAE ≈ 0.137, and R² ≈ 0.964. At certain stations, R² rises to ~0.99. Nonetheless, the decline of R² to ~0.91 at the weakest stations shows that LSTM is less stable than the boosting methods for short-term SPEI, while still tracking the overall tendencies quite well.
The SVR method attains results close to LSTM, with average RMSE ≈ 0.151, MAE ≈ 0.140, and R² ≈ 0.964. Although R² falls to ~0.87 at some stations, overall the results are consistent. While SVR can capture nonlinear relationships via kernel functions, hyperparameter sensitivity leads to inter-station performance fluctuations.
RF, in this study, is the lowest-performing method. With average RMSE ≈ 0.279, MAE ≈ 0.171, and R² ≈ 0.913, RF attains only limited success for short-horizon (1-month) SPEI forecasts. In particular, the drop of R² to ~0.82 at some stations indicates that this method remains weaker than boosting-based approaches.
Overall, for 1-month SPEI forecasting across Greece, boosting-based methods (GBM and XG) clearly stand out as the strongest models. LSTM and SVR form a second, yet strong, tier, performing well—especially in capturing nonlinear relationships. RF, by contrast, is better regarded as a supporting or benchmarking model due to its lower accuracy. In sum, for short-term SPEI, the most reliable and lowest-error models with the highest inter-station consistency are GBM and XG, while LSTM and SVR provide secondary but robust alternatives.
Table S1. Performance metrics for 1-month SPEI machine-learning results at stations in Greece

A.2. Model Predictive Performance for 6-Month SPEI
According to Table S2, a clear performance gap is observed among the machine-learning methods. GBM and XG stand out, delivering near-error-free forecasts with average RMSE ≈ 0.005, MAE ≈ 0.003, and R² ≈ 1.000. The extremely high consistency across stations indicates that these two boosting-based methods provide very strong reliability and generalizability for 6-month SPEI predictions.
The LSTM method exhibits very strong performance, with average RMSE ≈ 0.089, MAE ≈ 0.066, and R² ≈ 0.991. At some stations, R² reaches ~0.998, and even the lowest values remain around ~0.965, demonstrating robust generalization. However, the higher error rates relative to the boosting methods suggest that, at this horizon, LSTM is more limited in capturing short-term fluctuations.
SVR trails LSTM but still yields satisfactory results overall, with average RMSE ≈ 0.170, MAE ≈ 0.150, and R² ≈ 0.967. That said, R² drops to ~0.885 at certain stations, indicating pronounced sensitivity to parameter choices and greater inter-station variability.
RF records the lowest performance among the methods. With average RMSE ≈ 0.220, MAE ≈ 0.127, and R² ≈ 0.949, it produces weaker outcomes than the other models; in some stations, R² declines to ~0.889, showing that RF cannot capture the complex relationships in 6-month SPEI series as effectively as the boosting approaches.
Overall, for 6-month SPEI forecasting, GBM and XG are the strongest and most reliable methods. Their low error values and high R² make them the most suitable candidates for operational use. Leveraging its long-memory architecture, LSTM emerges as a strong alternative; SVR is moderately successful but more variable across stations. RF is best viewed as a comparative/benchmark method, given its comparatively limited predictive performance. In sum, the superiority of boosting-based methods is once again clearly evident for 6-month SPEI forecasts.
Table S2. Performance metrics for 6-month SPEI machine-learning results at stations in Greece
 
 A.3. Model Predictive Performance for 12-Month SPEI
According to Table S3, GBM and XG once again stand out as the clearly best-performing models. These two boosting-based approaches reduce average RMSE to 0.002–0.005 and MAE to 0.002–0.003, while driving R² to ~1.000 at nearly all stations. The combination of very low errors and high inter-station consistency makes GBM and XG the most reliable methods operationally for 12-month SPEI forecasts.
The LSTM method delivers very strong performance with average RMSE ≈ 0.070, MAE ≈ 0.053, and R² ≈ 0.994. At many stations, R² exceeds 0.995, and even the lowest values remain around 0.981, indicating that LSTM is a strong model for long-horizon SPEI. However, compared with the boosting methods, its higher error rates show that LSTM does not capture fluctuations at this scale as perfectly as GBM/XG.
SVR ranks third, with average RMSE ≈ 0.206, MAE ≈ 0.189, and R² ≈ 0.945. At some stations, R² drops to ~0.86, indicating weakened predictive power in certain areas. Sensitivity to kernel choice and parameter settings emerges as the primary reason for inter-station performance differences in SVR.
RF shows the lowest performance. With average RMSE ≈ 0.192, MAE ≈ 0.121, and R² ≈ 0.953, RF can track general tendencies but remains noticeably weaker than the boosting methods and LSTM. Moreover, inter-station variability further reduces RF’s consistency.
Overall, for 12-month SPEI prediction, GBM and XG are the most powerful and reliable methods. LSTM provides a very strong alternative just behind these two, whereas SVR and RF remain supporting models due to their lower accuracy. The results clearly demonstrate the superiority of boosting-based methods in long-term SPEI forecasting and indicate that, thanks to their stability across stations and high accuracy, these models should be the primary choice for both operational and academic applications.
