A.4. Model Predictive Performance for 1-Month RDI
According to Table S4, clear differences are observed among the machine-learning methods. First, at several stations—Ierapetra, Milos, Naxos, Rhodos, among others—LSTM, GBM, SVR, and XG exhibit extremely large error values in the RMSE and MAE metrics. This indicates that, at those stations, these methods can yield unstable results due to overfitting, data scaling, or computational issues. Nevertheless, when the overall averages are considered, a clear performance ranking still emerges.
Excluding the stations noted above, GBM and XG generally deliver the best results. At most stations, R² reaches 1.000, with a decline to about 0.85 only at Souda. This finding suggests that boosting-based methods exhibit strong stability for 1-month RDI forecasts, but that data-related imbalances at specific stations can depress performance.
LSTM attains extremely high average values—RMSE ≈ 1.09×1033 and MAE ≈ 9.83×1032—producing serious model instabilities at some stations. However, where errors remain within normal ranges, R² rises to ~0.99, indicating that, although LSTM is theoretically powerful, it fails to deliver stable outcomes on short-horizon (1-month) RDI due to parameter sensitivity.
SVR likewise produces anomalously large errors (around 1036) at certain stations. With average RMSE ≈ 1.67×1035 and MAE ≈ 1.67×1035, the model fails particularly at noisy and variable stations. Even so, at stations with more regular behavior, R² remains in the 0.90–0.99 range, showing that SVR can yield strong results under specific conditions, albeit inconsistently for 1-month RDI.
RF is more stable overall, with average RMSE ≈ 0.38, MAE ≈ 0.30, and R² ≈ 0.71. While RF does not generate the extreme outliers seen in other methods, it lags well behind boosting approaches in accuracy. In short-term RDI prediction, RF fails to adequately capture complex inter-station relationships, with R² often remaining in the 0.60–0.75 band across many stations.
In summary, for 1-month RDI forecasts in Greece, GBM and XG are the most successful and reliable methods. Although LSTM and SVR can achieve high accuracy at some stations, they are not dependable due to serious instabilities. RF is more consistent but operates with lower accuracy. Overall, the superiority of boosting-based methods is reaffirmed; however, from the standpoint of model stability, data preprocessing, station-specific parameter optimization, and error-balancing strategies are critical.
Table S4. Performance metrics for 1-month RDI machine-learning results at stations in Greece

A.5. Model Predictive Performance for 6-Month RDI
According to Table S5, a clear performance gap again emerges among the machine-learning methods. GBM and XG produce the lowest error rates—average RMSE ≈ 0.006–0.008, MAE ≈ 0.001–0.004—and attain R² ≈ 1.000. In particular, XG delivers near-error-free results across virtually all stations, keeping R² close to 1.000, which makes it the most reliable model for 6-month RDI forecasts. GBM shows similarly consistent performance, clearly underscoring the superiority of boosting-based methods.
The LSTM method performs well with average RMSE ≈ 0.168, MAE ≈ 0.092, and R² ≈ 0.957. At some stations, R² climbs to ~0.99, while the lowest values fall to ~0.885. This indicates that LSTM generally captures long-term tendencies effectively, albeit with some inter-station variability. Even so, LSTM remains a strong alternative following the boosting methods.
SVR exhibits moderate performance—average RMSE ≈ 0.276, MAE ≈ 0.220, and R² ≈ 0.908. Although it achieves strong results at certain stations, R² drops to ~0.78–0.82 at others, signaling lower stability across stations. Sensitivity to kernel choice and limitations in capturing short-term fluctuations likely drive these differences.
RF also shows lower performance, close to SVR: average RMSE ≈ 0.257, MAE ≈ 0.095, and R² ≈ 0.933. While RF can track general tendencies, the decline of R² to ~0.86 at some stations indicates that RF is less effective than boosting methods in modeling complex, long-duration dependencies for 6-month RDI.
Overall, for 6-month RDI forecasts, the boosting-based models (GBM and XG) are the most successful and reliable, delivering both low errors and high inter-station consistency. LSTM stands out as a strong alternative, whereas SVR and RF exhibit somewhat weaker performance.
Table S5. Performance metrics for 6-month RDI machine-learning results at stations in Greece
 
A.6. Model Predictive Performance for 12-Month RDI
According to Table S6, a clear performance ranking again emerges among the machine-learning methods. GBM and XG achieve the lowest error rates—average RMSE ≈ 0.003–0.014, MAE ≈ 0.001–0.006—and the highest explanatory power with R² ≈ 1.000. These two boosting-based models deliver near-error-free results at almost all stations and ensure top-level inter-station consistency. Accordingly, for 12-month RDI forecasts, GBM and XG are the most reliable and operationally applicable methods.
The LSTM method shows strong performance with average RMSE ≈ 0.149, MAE ≈ 0.060, and R² ≈ 0.962. While R² reaches 0.98–1.00 at many stations, it declines to ~0.87–0.90 at some. These results indicate that, thanks to its long-memory architecture, LSTM captures drought tendencies and seasonal patterns well, but exhibits greater inter-station variability than the boosting methods.
SVR performs more modestly, with average RMSE ≈ 0.302, MAE ≈ 0.227, and R² ≈ 0.898. Although it produces strong outcomes at certain stations, the fact that R² dips below 0.85 at many stations suggests that SVR is unstable and inconsistent for long-horizon RDI forecasting.
RF is generally more consistent than SVR but lags the boosting methods in accuracy. With average RMSE ≈ 0.156, MAE ≈ 0.035, and R² ≈ 0.972, RF can track overall tendencies, yet is less successful than GBM and XG for 12-month RDI prediction. Its broader error spread across stations further indicates difficulty in fully modeling long-duration dependencies.
Overall, for 12-month RDI forecasts, GBM and XG are the top-performing models. LSTM and RF follow as strong alternatives, whereas SVR remains the weakest due to its instability and lower accuracy. These results once again confirm the reliability of boosting-based methods for long-term drought forecasting, demonstrating that—especially for a more complex index like RDI—they are the most suitable choices for operational deployment.
